{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_goblin_ver01/data/sn82015425/00529040982/1958052301/0845.xml":{"full_text":"K\nAlthea Gibson, the Wimbledon and U S. tennis champion,\nmoke-, her singing debut on the Ed Sullivan Show next Sunday.\nNR^ and Sport magazine have profiles on the ex-Florida A&M\nstar Now fork fans are getting plenty of major league\nba'cboll television. Gothan fans were treated to six games\u2014\nthree double headers on three different channels Grambling\nCollege and Jackson State hove transferred from NAIA Dis-\nIrirt 29 to MAIA District 6, which is made up of the SIAC, South\nwe i, Gulf Coast, SEAC and South Central loop\nA good publicist can d<> more with\npersonality than a trained psy\nchiatrist. For example, newspaper\nmen a few months ago were des\ncribing Althea Gibson as \u201carri\ngant.\" \u201cmoody,\u201d ''temperamental,\"\n\u201ctactless,\" \u201cTe^ Williams without\nskills\" and \u201cJackie Robinson with\nout charm.\" Well. Miss Gibson is\nnow being well-managed b. v a big\nrecording firm, who views her\ncareer as paralleling that of Sam\nCooke, the ex-Soul Stirrer.\no o \u2014\u2014o\nSpent magazine nows sobs a com\noleic reversal of character lias\ntaken place. This girl with her de\nfenses up\u2014this girl who had been\ndistant and disparaging to news\npapermen, aloof an^ abrupt to those\nwho sought her friendship, who\nalways presented a disdainfully\ncocksure picture of herself\u2014this\ngirl suddenly blossomed into a\npoised lady both on and off the'\ntennis court.\no o o\n\"It was if, her public mission\nhaving been accomplished, her pri\nvate demons were assuaged. And at\nthe age of 30, Althea was finally\nable to discard her chip-on-the\nshoulder adolescence and behave\nwith the accents of maturity.\"\nO O 0\nCBS is likewise spelling out Miss\nGibson\u2019s virtues tor hw TV sing\ning debut Sunday night on the Ed\nSulliVan Show, j still believe that\na good publicist w ill outdo the most\ngjped psychiatrist.\no\u2014o- o\nLIVING IT UP: When Sugar Ray\nRobinson arrived in Chicago, Till.,\nto meet Carmen Basilio for middle\nweight championship, he brought;\nwith him the built-in, old-style I\nshowmanship that marked the Joe j\nLouis years. j\nThere were 16 in the Sugar Ray's\nparty that arrived in the Windy\nCity before the fight\u2014Robinson,\nwife Edna Mae. two managers, one\nmanager\u2019s wife, two trainers, a New\nYork detective serving as Ray\u2019s\nbodyguard, a rubdown man. per\nsonal physician Vincent Nardiellc\nand his wife, three sparring part\nners. laywer Martin Machat. a\ncamp secretary, and a press agent. I\nThe rate few Ray's own suite\u2014twin I\nbedrooms and a parlor the length\nof oitp wing of the hotel\u2014was $BO\na dav.\n\u2022Sugar Ray carried just as im- I\npress! w and entourage to Europe. j\nwhen he met and tost his title to\nRandy TuPpm Champions come\nand go. but for my money, no man\nin modern times has rivaled the\nflail, charm and showmanship. that\nRobinson and I mtis eave then\nchampionship\nRobinson's spectacular living is\nso fabulous that it excites and elec\ntirifics the whole nation when a\nfight is on deck. His mode of living\nis terrific I\no o o\nHERE AND THERE: Dame Fate\noften decrees tragedy and misfort\nune. The fickle wand of destiny\nstruck both the Dodgers and Giants\nfollowing their switch to the West\nCoast. Evil luck has haunted both\nclubs since the transfer. It is grim\ncoincidence that both of the clubs\nare affected by auto accidents. Roy\nCampanella was seriously injured\nonly a few blocks from his home.\nPete Stoneham of th c Giants was\nInvolved hi an accident which cost\nthe life of a woman in Phoenix,\nArizona.\nCampy may neve r walk again\nend while many offer prayer that\nhe will the prosj>ccts of recovery\nwill linger long nast his playing\ndays. Stoneham, 30-year-old son of\nthe Giants\u2019 owner and heir to the\nclub presidency, and Horace, his\nfather face a $500,000 civil suit over\nthe accident in which Pete's car\nhit the other car heads on. The\nhusband of the deceased women is\na wealthy Canadian and has hired\na battery of four lawyers to fight\nfor a verdict against Stoneham.\no o o\nHERE AND THERE: Dr. Ben\njamin E. Mays will open the At\nlanta campaign of the United Ne\npro College Fund. Thursday, June\n5. The drive will benefit Clark.\nMorehouse, Morris Brown. Spel\nman, Gammon Theological Semin\nary, and Atlanta University. All\ncommunity agencies should begin\nspadework towards supporting this\nvital effort Resigned to a-id the 33\nJEAN WORTH\nDon't Be Misled\nLook The Nome\nJEAN WORTH\nOn Sign\nCat-h Suburban bu\u00ab rotns\nFairborn Broad and Alabama St-,,\nand gel \"ff Oak Ga al Ihr\ntraffic li\u00abh<- Ix>ek for sign of JI AN\nW R ^TICE ON SUNDAYS OK\nHOLIDAYS\nTake College Park Trolley to Col\nlege Park and change to FairUarn\nB Closed Wednesdays\nThis lady does not flatter you\ntells your life as it is. and should\nbe. For every trouble there is a rem\nedy, and in most cases, the remedy\nis within your reach, if you only\nknow how. For while ignorance may\nsometimes be bliss, it is folly of the\n\u201cost dangerous sort to be\nof the problems of Lovo. Marriage.\nBusiness and Speculation.\nShe answers many questions. Kuy\n\u2666hyself and find Success and Wappt\nweM. Ne one in trouble turned away.\nThis Udp haa.helPed thousands and\nahe can and will nelp yon-\nThis lady Warns xM rrsvelr\nHSl.esssctbof\u201cBSJ!Ss\nPARK, GEORGIA\nI nrivate colleges, mestiy in the\nSouth\nO o\nMorris Brown assistant coach\nWilliam T. Greene did a fine job\nof directing the college physical\neducation and athletic programs\nduring the illness of Head Coach\nE. J. Clemons. He was staunchly\nbacked by the Athletic Committee\nchairman A. J. Lockhart.\nBoth manfully shouldered thc\n(cad of carrying on an overall pro\ngram that embraced basketball and\ntrack, as well as intramurals. They\ndeserve the sincere thanks of all\nconcerned.\no O 0\nOUT AT CARVER VOCATION\nAL SCHOOL a week ago I had\nlunch with various captains of\nsports teams there. We chatted\nwith Principal Bohannon, Coach\nAlexander Shepar^ and his staff\nand a sprinkling of faculty mem\nbers,\no o o\nThe occasion was the annual\n\u201cPlay Day\u201d and the areas abounded\nwith good humor, shrill cries of\njoy, and the lightheartedness of our\nyoung.\nCarver Vocational School enjoy\ned an enviable year in athletic ac\ncomplishments. Yet towering above\nthis achievement was some remark\nable character building. I have\nwatched personnel of Carver Voca\ntional School athletic teams on the\nstreets, in the gymnasiums, and on\nthe highways and byways of life.\nThey\u2019re certainly shown remark\nable mental and cultural improve\nment.\no o o\nSeveral of the fellows told me\nthey planned to go to college. I\nhope so a good school is measured\nby tlh e success of its graduates\nAnd the best yardstick is his zeal\ntor higher education, marriage and\na- happy family.\nS. C. State Fetes\nAthletic Teams\nORANGEBURG. <8 C. The\nSouth Carolina State College cut\nurinated its athletic year with thc\nall-sports banquet last Wednesday\nnight with all athletes and then\nguests enjoying the festivities. Visit\ning coaches from Claflin, Voorhees.\nS. C A. T. S., North Carolina Col\nlege ,and Tennessee State were al\nhand to honor the \u201cBulldog's.\u201d\nJohnny B. McLendon, head bas\nketball coach at Tennessee State\ngave interesting accounts of his\nteams' participation in the NAIA\nbasketball tournament in Kansas\nCity. Other remarks were made oy\nPresident B. C. Turner, F. M. Sta\nley. and H. W. Crawford. Leo Ker\nford, instructor of law, was toast\nmaster. Roy D. Moore, athletic di\nrector, presented sweaters and\nmonograms to the following:\nFOOTBALL\nSweaters: Robert Beasley, James\nWashington. James Payton, Ernest\nSpann. Richard Maddox, Alton sa\nFerguson, David Jones, Samuel\nHines, Ernest Richardson, Lonnie\nHolman, Rudolph Caldwell, James\nGreen, and Lester Seays.\nMonograms: Razzie Smith, Carl\nRobinson. Joe Spikes, Henry Dixon\nSamuel Prioleau, Fletcher Waye,\nIsaac Arnold. Harry Nelson, Henry\nBrevard, Alexander Gardner. Fred\ndie Rogers, and Roy L. Hurst.\nBASKETBALL\nSweaters: Melvin Galloway. Hen\ni ry Washington, Earl Bennett, and\nGeorge Tapley.\nMonograms: Robert Wright, Lin-\nI coin Stephens, Clarence Loach.\nJohn Brown, and Edward Green.\nBASEBALL\nSweaters: Richard Sing 1 ton,\nRichard Fogel, Albert Green.\nMonograms: Roy Hurst, Harry\nri?lson, Samuel Prioleau, Robert\nDixon, Lewis Green, Willie Jef\nfeers, Nathaniel Phelps, Charles\nSmalls, and Lerov Ransom.\nTRACK\nSweaters: Thomas Mouzon, An\ndrew Rodrigues, and Julius New\nton.\nMonograms: Alexander Gardner.\nFreddie Rogers and Emanuel John\nsen.\nSweaters were also given to\nManager Paul Mack; Statistician\nMilton Davenport; and Cheerlead-\ners Barbara. Moye and Sophire\nWilson.\nThomson\nTHOMSON. Ga \u2014The first, grade\nof the McDuffie County Training\nSchool presented, an operetta \u201cThe\nMcCorkle and R Foster in charge\nAmonig those part-ioipa-ting were\nHomiest Gunby. William Howard,\nPriscilla Calhoun, students repre\nsenting the flowers, wind, snow and\nchorus\nMRS. DAY, Advisor\nI am a Christian woman and believe in telling the truth. If\nyou are sick, worried, in trouble, have obstacles or hidden fears;\nif you have love and marriage problems, I can and will help you\nwith all of your problems as I have helped thousands of others.\nTake the College Park bns at Alabama and Broad Streets,\nride to the end of the line in College Park and phone me. No\ncharge to pick you up. Located on Roosevelt Highway, Route 29.\nOpen from 7 A. M. to 11 P. M. Daily, Sunday and Holidays.\nFOR APPOINTMENTS AND DIRECTIONS:\nCall POplar 1-9277\nSI I\ngi\nRow 9\nWMMw\nCARVER WINS IRA JARRELL SPORTSMANSHIP\nTROPHY In the photo a group of athletes,\ncoaches and the principal of the George Wash\nington Carver Vocational High School are ^hown\nadmiring the beautiful Ira Jarrell\" w ay \u00bbnan\nship Trophy, This trophy, awarded^Y policy O n\nthe basis of the conduct of studen ,e Statio-j O us\nathletic events during the year, i by\nCarver Wins Irr Jarrell\nSportsmanship Trophy\nGciOTgc Waslungt'm Garver Vocu\ntional High School won the Ira\nJarrell Bportsman.ship Tr -phy for\nfor the best all-around !m\u2019-\nhavior of stodienks al. athletic event,'\nduring the year.\nThe winning of fins beautilul tro\nphy. awarded annually and nam\ned for the (illustrious superinten\ndent of the Atlanta. Public School\nSystem, is quite a climaxing ex\nperience for the principal, teach\ners and .student body at Caiwer.\nAll of the high schools in the\ncity are in competition for this\ntrophy, and the winner is selected\nby a committee from the Athletic\nDepartment trial checks on the con\nduct of students at all games Th s\ncommit Lee selected Carver as the\nrecipient of this distinct, honor foi\n195\u00ae\nSince the beginning of this award.\nMost Ring Champions From\nRanks Of Underprivileged\nNEW YORK. UNS' Vir\ntually every ring champion in his\ntory enme from the ranks of the\npoor and underpanviliged.\nIn the early days thc English\nhad a monopoly on what they were\npleased to call th c \u201csweet science.\"\nThen the boys of Irish descent\nsuch as John L. Sullivan. James\nJ. f\u2019orheH and Jack McAuliffe took\nover, and for a long time most, o*\nthe ton notchcrs had Irish ances\ntors.\nNext poor Jewish boys like Benny\nLeonard took to the ring and made\ngood in a big way. Right along\nwith them wore hundredis of Italiasi\nboys.\nThere always have been occas\nional great Negro fighters such as\nGeorge Dixon, Joe Gans and Jack\nJohnson. But it was not until Joe\nLouis became heavyweight champ\nion that his race took to the ring\nin overwhelming droves. Now- per\nhaps 80 per cent of the fighters\nin this country are Negroes.\nBoys in other countries heard\n\u2022ibout. the fortunes being made in\nboxing, and within the last 30 years\nwe have had more than a score of\nnaibionalities represented among th r\nworld champions\u2014either boys born\nabroad or whoise parents were born\noutside the United States.\nLet's see how well you know your\nring champions. Just name a world\nchampion of the following nation\nalities: lArgentikie. Japanese. FIG\npino. Algerian. Nigerian, French.\nIrish Italian, English. Scotch,\nWelsh. German. Polish, Lithuanian,\nSyrian. Spanish, Croatian. Czecho\nslovakian, Mexican, Russian. Dan\nish, Australian an<j South African.\nOf course, if you are a fiighit fan\nyou undoubtedly were aware that\nFreddie Zivic was of Croatian des-\nCarver for 1958. This group includes: Front row\n'I to r): Coach A. G. Shepard, Robert Lee, Miss\nThera Williams, Frank Browning, Miss Fronnie\nTucker, and Principal J. H. Bohannon. Back\nrow (I to r): Grady Sims, Herbert McDowell and\nCoach C. C. Williams. (Photo by Charles W.\nLowe).\nshe Henry 'McNomI 'rmnci lh:h\nSchoo! has had 'lie plrc^u of\nwinning the trophy each year\nOTHER LAI RELS\nIn addition to winning this honor\nCarver won the city champ'onship\nin football, city and .'\"late cham\npionships in basketball and was\ninvited to participate in Mie Na\ntional High School Basketball\nTournament, held annually at. Ten\nnessee State A. and T. University.\nNashville, Tenn.; second place m\nthe city-wide track and (roll events\nMiss Fronnie Tucker, a sopho\nmore, distinguished herself in uch\na line manner al flic Tuskegee Re\nlays she has been invited to run\nwith the Tennessee Slate Uir.versif.x\nTigcrbelles in the National Wom\nen\u2019s Track and Field 'Meet <AAU>\nthis .summer.\ncent; Pauro Salas, Mexican, and\nAl Host ok, Czech o-slovakia n\nAnd it\u2019s probable thaf you knew\nBilly Sense was of Hungarian ex\n\u00ab.fact\u2019on; Bait Nelson, Danish; SAan\nKoschei, Polish; Jack Sharkey, Lit\nhuianlain, and Gus Lesnevfioh, Russ\nian\nIt w\u2019Hil,) not surprise us to find\nvou knew that Baltazar Sangchilb\nwas Spanish; Primo Camera. Ital\nian: Max Schmeling, German, and\nliattling Siki a Sengalesc. But did\nvou know that Petey Sarron\u2019s folk\nhailed from Syria?\nNow we have a new fistic harvest\ncoming from various parts of Af\nrica, an uprising that was started\nwhen Marcel Cerdan from Algeria\nbecame middleweight champion.\nSince then we have Vic Toweel,\nfrom SoutGi Africa, Robert Coheci\nand Alphone Halimi from Algeria,\nand Kid Bassey from Nigeria all\nwinning world titles. And in Madi\nson Square Garden Friday we will\nsee an-ather Algerian, lightweight\nLahouri Gcdhi, who is meeting\nJohnny Busso.\nMilledgeville\nMilledgeville ,Ga.\u2014 The drive at\nthe Wesley Chapel AME Church\nclosed on Sunday. A total of $1301.-\n49 was reported. The Board of Re\nigious Education will meet with\nMrs. Bertha Cbllier on Thursday\nevening at 8 o\u2019clockj Mrs. C. W\nBoddie is.the oresidehit. The Jun-\nAnnouncement..,\nThe Georgia Motor Club\n(AAA) proudly announces\nthat full, low cost member\nships are now available to all\nthe colored car owners in the\nAtlanta area. You can save\nlots of time, money and wor\nry with our services and pro\ntection. For full details on\nhow you can benefit, and a\nfree large map of USA,\nCALL\n808 MURPHY\nNOW AT\nTR. 5-7171\nNo Obligation. Of Course.\nCalloway Cubs And\nMarietta Orioles\nSplit Doublebill\nTile Galloway Cubs, of LaGrange,\nGa. and tlhe Maripti\u2019a Orioles split\na reorgia-Al'.bam a Amateur Base\nball League dOuibleheaider, Satur\nday. ad Lariry Bell Park, Marietta,\nGa\nAfter dropping the opejier, 13-8,\n\u2018he cubs bounced back and won\ntihe niightx\u2019ap, 7-5 Willie Bolds amd\nCurtis McCrary fortned tihe battery\ntor the Cubs in the opener.\nSammy Catton went- to the\nniound for the Cubs in the night\n\u2022:ap. with MteCiiary again working\nbehind tihe plate. Robert. Cotton\n'ame through with another home\nrim in the sixth, which cleared the\nceiitorfield fence. Miorris Williams\nam e up wi th a. greaf ca kih for\n\u0964he Cutbs.\nThe Cubs now have a 2-and-2\necord.\nN. C. A&T Nine Wins\nOver Fayetteville\nState In Final Game\nGREENSBORO. N. C. Thc\nA&T College Aggies closed out the\nbaseball season last Friday with a\n6-4 win over Fayetteville Stoto\nTeachers College.\nThe game, played her e at Me\nmiorial Stadium, was a close con\niesl until the sixth frame when the\nAggies blasted in three-runs to\ntake tih e lead for good.\nThe winning pitcher was Aussie\nBroadnax, the loser was Robert\nGordon. Both went the distance.\nThe win gave the Aggies a 9-4\nreeor^ for the e ^on.\nFatal Beating\nConviction\nBrings 2 Years\nA two-year prison sentence was\ngiven a 37-year-o\u2019d man late Wed\nnesday after a Superior Court jwy\nfound him guilty of involuntary\nmanslaughter in connection with\nthe fatal beating of a women last\nmonth.\nHerman Russell, of 111 Postel\nSt. .was sentenced by Judge Jesse\nM. Wood after the jury reduced\nhis sentence from murder to in\nvoluntary manslaughter.\nRussell was accused of beating to\ndeath Miss Lottie Mae Jackson, of\na Postel Street address, on April\n13 Before the woman died the next\nday, she named Russell as her as\nsailant, witnesses said.\nA Fulton County Grand Jury\ncharged Russell with beating thc\nwoman with his fists and with an\nunknown blunt, instrument The in\ndictment also said he dropped her\nbody on the ground \"thereby in\nflicting upon her mortal wounds\nfrom which sh P died.\u201d\nior Missionary Society met on Sun\nday afternoon with Mrs. Lucy Den\nnis. Mrs. Tressie Evans, president.\nStewardess Board No. 1 met with\nMrs. Virginia Waller Sunday after\nnoon.\nMrs. Ellen Hurst died at a local\nhospital recently. Her funeral was\nheld on Sunday at the County Line\nBiapltist Church. The funeral of\nMr. Dorsey Pitts was held at Brown\nChapel CMJE Church. Mi\u2019S- Leila\nYon mg died suddenly on Monday\nmorning. She is a member of the\nTrinity OME Church. Funeral ar\nrangements will be announce^ la\nter. Mr. David Evans is at the Ve\nterans Administration Hospital\nDublin.\nN. Y. Yankees Hand Detroit\nTigers Bth Straight Loss\nDETROIT (INS) M a v\nThraneberry s ninth inning horn\ner earned the New York Yan\nkees their ninth straight victory\ntoday as they beat the Detroit\nTigers, 5 to 4.\nIt was the Tigers\u2019 eighth straight\ndefeait and d: cjped them to last\nplace in the American League\nstand'ngs.\nThcrnebciiry, a .212 hitter subb\ning for th e injured Bill Skowron,\nblasted his homor as leadoff man\nfor t'he Yanks in the ninth.\nDeitroit's Gus Zernial had tied the\nscore in the eighth inning when he\ncTouitCf] the ighth p\u2019meh-hit round\ntripper of his career. Zernial Croke\nthe American Leiague record oi\nseven which he had shared with\nTed Williams of the Boston Red\nSox.\nZernial's blow was the only hit\nallowed by fireball reliefer Ryne\nN. C. College\nNetters Win\nCIAA Crown\nRICHMOND, Va. North Caro\nlina Coi\u2019ege's tennis team copped\nthe CIAA tennis championship at\nUnion University last week en^ as\nthey racked up 13 points to second\nplace Hampton Institute\u2019s 12 points\nThis was Coach Jimmy Younge\u2019s\ntennis squad\u2019s second straight\nchampionship, having tied Hamp\nton fcr the crown last year. For\nthe first time since \u201853 Hampton\nCoach Herman Neilson\u2019s Pirates\nwere shut out of a conference crown.\nT'he Eagles\u2019 two doubles teams\nclashed in the finals with Dorian\nParreabt and Malcolm Little up\nsetting tire tourney\u2019s top-seeded duo\nof Mauric e Handy and Napoleon\nHorton, 6-4, 6-3.\nParreott and Little advanced to\n\u2018he finals by downing Jerry Napper\nand Bob Dowdy of J. C Smith, 6-4,\n5-7, 6-L Handy and Hcrton mowed\ndawn Gene Donan and William\nMerritt of Hampton, 5-7, 6-3, 6-1\nbefore going into the finals.\nPanreoitt, too-seeded singles netter\nin the three day net tourney, play\ning for the first time after a long\nlay-off. was knocked off in the\nquarter finals by un-seeded William\nColeman of Morgan State. 7-5, 6-2.\nColeman was topple^ by Hamp\nton's Gene Donan to advance to\nthe finials against his teammate,\nsecond seeded James Stroud, mak\ning it an all-Pirate singles finals\nStroud advanced to the finals bl'\nbeating Bill Butler of Morgan, wire\ndowned NCC\u2019s Carlton Bell in the\nquarter finals, 7-5, 6-3. Stroud beat\nButler 6-3, 6-1, and followed up by\nttppliing Donan in the finals.\nOther conference teams partici\npating in tiie tournament were\nMorgan State, J. C- Smith, Blue\nfield, Virginia Union, Howard Uni\nversity, and Shaw University.\nTheodosius Bush To\nRun In NAIA Track,\nField Meet, June 6-7\nKANSAS CITY. Mo. Theodos\nius Bush of Texas Southern Uni\nversity will have the most experi\nence of any dash man in the\nseventh annual National Associat\nion of Intercollegiate Athletics\nbrack and field championships in\nSan Diego June 6-7\u2014if he can just\nremember.\nBush won the 100 and 220-yard\ndashes in the 1953 NAIA meet, and\nfinished second behind teammate\nRalph Aldredgc in the 1954 century.\nHe failed to finish the 220 that\nyeai- because of a pulled muscle.\nSince then he has spent some\ntime in military service, but he\u2019s\nback in college and entered in the\n1958 NAIA meet.\nAnj help if he can re-\nmember that 1953 winning time. A\n:09.6 would do pretty well even\nnow.\nHartwell\nHARTWELL, Ga\u2014The Sardis\nBaptist Church will observe its pas\nter, Rev. F. E- Harrell\u2019s anniversary\non Sunday. Rev. S. S. Brewer will\nbe guest speaker. Children\u2019s Day\nwill be held on the second Sunday\nin June at the Sardis Baptist Church\nAll churches are invited. Mr. and\nMrs. Edward- Dee Roebuck an\nnounce the birth of a baby girl\nJanice Elaine on May 15. Please\nGive News To E. L. Roebuck each\nweek.\nED SAMPLES\nAUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION\nSERVICE\nAny Make Any Model\n3-HOUR SERVICE\nE-Z TERMS\nDIAL TR. $-St3l\n887 Marietta St., NW\nATLANTA BALLY WORLD FrUgSy, My 53, 1958\nMarv Threneberry\nHomers B@mbpr^ \u00a9ver\nFading Tigers, 5-4\nDuren of the Yanks, who pitched\nthe Ja\u2018t three innings and struck\nout five to earn his first majoi\nleague victory.\nNew York starter Bobby Shantz\nwho lia,d beaten the Tigers 12\nsitraighi' times, was removed in the\nsixth inning.\nOn'y two of th e Yanks\u2019 runs off\nloser Paul Foytack were earned, as\nthe Tigers made two critical errors\nCHISOX END FOUR GAME\nLOSING STREAK BEATING\nBALTIMORE ORIOLES, 5-1\nCHICAGO. (INS) The Chi\ncago White Sox, smarting from a\nverbal blast bv club vice president\nChuck Comiskey, broke a four\ngame losing streak Thursday as\nveteran righthander Jim Wilson\nbeat the Baltimore Orioles, 5 to 1.\nWinston-Salem Takes First\nPlace In Carolinas' AAU\nRALEIGH \u2014Winston-Salem State\nTeachers College won th e Annua!\nCaro!nas\u2019 AAU Track and Field\nChampionship with 49 points, piling\nup 31 of them in the hurdles events\nalone.\nNorth Carolina College swept six\nfirsts places fcr a total of 40 points\nto finish second.\nThe jewel of the meet was Elias\nGilbert\u2019s world-record shattering\nperformance in the 220 low hurd\nles. Th e Ram hurdler was clocked\nin 22.1, clipping one-tenth second\noff the previous world record held\nby Duke\u2019s Dave Sime.\nThe most thrilling performance\nof th e night was NCC\u2019s Vance\nRobinson\u2019s upset victory over the\nfamed Duke speedster in the 100\n.yard dash.\nThe Sime-conscious press here in\nCarolina failed to even give an ac\ncurate account of the event, play\ning up Sime\u2019s injury and failing\nto even recognize Robinson's blaz\ning time in the victory which he\nwon in 95 easily.\nSpectators at th e meet know that\nthe Eagles\u2019 Robinson caught up\nwith Sime at the 50 yard mark and\nran neck and neck for the next 20\nyards before Robinson went slight\nly ahead of the world's supposedly\nfastest human. At th e 80 yard\nmarker when Sime pulled up lame\nRobinson had a slight edge on him.\nRobinson left lititl e doubt in the\ncrowd's minds as to his greatness\nby coming back to win the 200 yard\ndash in a fast-stepping 20.8\nNCC\u2019s Louis Seaton finished be\nhind Robinson and Wesley Baldwin\nof A&T in the century event, clock\ned in 9.8. Bobby Dobbs finished in\nthird spot in the 220 vard dash\nbehind his more illustaious team-\nmate. Dobbs\u2019 time was 21.7.\nAlthough slighted bv the daily\npress, NCC\u2019s two quarter-miler;\ncontinued to prove tiiat they arc\nthe best frosh in that event in the\ncountry, as well as he beat in the\nsouthern part of the United States\nby winning tire 440 yard' dash in i\n1-2 order.\nWalter Johnson, a freshman from\nNew Haven, Conn., snapped the\ntape just inches ahead of his team\nmate. Ken Riley, to win the 440\nevent in new meet record time ol\n48.0, followed by Riley\u2019s 48.1.\nJohnson continues to amaze every\none with his exploits in that this\nis his first year running track any\nwhere. Juist last week he posted a\n47.8 in the conference chamption\nships to give him the best time of\nany first year quarter -miler in the\ncountry.\nIn the 880 yard run Coach L. T.\nWalker\u2019s harriers also dominated,\nwith Neville Christian sailing\nacross the tape first in 1:53.9. and\nhis running cronie, William Ward,\nYEARS OLD ^1\n86\nPROOF 1\nsK\ni uo\nI j\u00ae.\u00ae\nz X:-\nHEAVEN HILL\nJhe tanpsf Selling Bourbon\nin Kentucky,\nr where Bourbon wos bornl\nComiskey had blasted the team\nfor what he called its \u201clackadaisi\ncal\" play and said be hoped the\nnlayers would read what he said\nin the newspapers and \u201csnap out\nof their dreams.\u201d\nWilson went the distance to re\ncord his fourth win of the year\nagainst three defeats. He lost his\nchia nee for a shutout in the nintli\ninn ng when the Orioles took ad\nvaicitage of two errors anj Foster\nCastleman\u2019s single to score a ran\nA chilled crowd of 632, the small\nest gathering to see a game at\nComiskey Park since May 7, 1943.\nwitnessed the game and was buf\nfeted by wind gusts up to 40 miles\nper hour.\nThe White Sox registered cue\nrun in the second inning without\nthe aijj of a hit and two mor e